<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="../../w/index-title=Melvyn_Bragg&action=edit&section=1.php.html" title="Edit section: Background">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Background">Background</span></h2>
<p>Bragg was born on 6 October 1939 in <a href="Carlisle,_Cumbria" title="Carlisle, Cumbria">Carlisle</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-mbceotv_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-mbceotv-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> the son of Mary Ethel (<i>née</i> Park), a tailor, and Stanley Bragg, a stock keeper turned mechanic.<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3"><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup> He attended the <a href="Nelson_Thomlinson_School" title="Nelson Thomlinson School" class="mw-redirect">Nelson Thomlinson School</a> in <a href="Wigton" title="Wigton">Wigton</a><sup id="cite_ref-mbceotv_2-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-mbceotv-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> and read <a href="Modern_History" title="Modern History" class="mw-redirect">Modern History</a> at <a href="Wadham_College,_Oxford" title="Wadham College, Oxford">Wadham College, Oxford</a> in the late 1950s and early 1960s.</p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="../../w/index-title=Melvyn_Bragg&action=edit&section=2.php.html" title="Edit section: Broadcasting career">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Broadcasting_career">Broadcasting career</span></h2>
<p>Bragg began his career in 1961 as a general trainee at the <a href="BBC" title="BBC">BBC</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-mbceotv_2-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-mbceotv-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> spending his first two years in radio at the <a href="BBC_World_Service" title="BBC World Service">BBC World Service</a>, then at the <a href="BBC_Third_Programme" title="BBC Third Programme">BBC Third Programme</a> and <a href="BBC_Home_Service" title="BBC Home Service">BBC Home Service</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Mensa1_4-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Mensa1-4"><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup> He then joined the production team of <a href="Huw_Wheldon" title="Huw Wheldon">Huw Wheldon</a>'s <i><a href="Monitor_(arts_programme)" title="Monitor (arts programme)" class="mw-redirect">Monitor</a></i> arts series on <a href="BBC_Television" title="BBC Television">BBC Television</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Mensa1_4-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Mensa1-4"><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup> and won an award for his screenplay on Debussy. He presented the BBC arts show <i>The Lively Arts</i>, a series that included the first ever televised documentary on <i><a href="Doctor_Who" title="Doctor Who">Doctor Who</a></i> broadcast in 1977, <i><a href="Whose_Doctor_Who" title="Whose Doctor Who">Whose Doctor Who</a></i>. His work as a writer and <a href="Presenter" title="Presenter">broadcaster</a> began in 1967. He is best known for the <a href="London_Weekend_Television" title="London Weekend Television">London Weekend Television</a> (LWT) arts programme <i><a href="The_South_Bank_Show" title="The South Bank Show">The South Bank Show</a></i>, which he edited and presented from 1978 to 2010.<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5"><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup> He was Head of Arts at LWT from 1982 to 1990 and Controller of Arts at LWT from 1990. He is also known for his many programmes on <a href="BBC_Radio_4" title="BBC Radio 4">BBC Radio 4</a>, including <i><a href="Start_the_Week" title="Start the Week">Start the Week</a></i> (1988 to 1998),<sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6"><span>[</span>6<span>]</span></a></sup> <i>The Routes of English</i>, (mapping the history of the English language), and <i><a href="In_Our_Time_(BBC_Radio_4)" title="In Our Time (BBC Radio 4)">In Our Time</a></i> (1998 to present), which in March 2011 broadcast its 500th programme. In February 2012, he began <i><a href="Melvyn_Bragg_on_Class_and_Culture" title="Melvyn Bragg on Class and Culture">Melvyn Bragg on Class and Culture</a></i>, a three-part series on BBC2 examining popular media culture with an analysis of the British social class system.<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7"><span>[</span>7<span>]</span></a></sup> In 2012 he brought back The South Bank Show to Sky Arts 1. In December 2012, he began <i><a href="../../w/index-title=The_Value_of_Culture&action=edit&redlink=1.php.html" class="new" title="The Value of Culture (page does not exist)">The Value of Culture</a></i>, a five-part series on BBC Radio 4 examining the meaning of culture, expanding on Matthew Arnold's landmark (1869) collection of essays <a href="Culture_and_Anarchy" title="Culture and Anarchy">Culture and Anarchy</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-8"><span>[</span>8<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>A novelist and writer of non-fiction, Bragg has written a number of television and film screenplays. Some of his early television work was in collaboration with <a href="Ken_Russell" title="Ken Russell">Ken Russell</a>, for whom he wrote the biographical dramas <i>The Debussy Film</i> (1965) and <i><a href="Isadora_Duncan,_the_Biggest_Dancer_in_the_World" title="Isadora Duncan, the Biggest Dancer in the World">Isadora Duncan, the Biggest Dancer in the World</a></i> (1967), as well as Russell's film about <a href="Tchaikovsky" title="Tchaikovsky" class="mw-redirect">Tchaikovsky</a>, <i><a href="The_Music_Lovers" title="The Music Lovers">The Music Lovers</a></i> (1970). He is president of the <a href="National_Academy_of_Writing" title="National Academy of Writing" class="mw-redirect">National Academy of Writing</a>. His 2008 novel <i>Remember Me</i> is part of a series of autobiographical fictions.</p>
<p>Bragg is a Vice President of the <a href="Friends_of_the_British_Library" title="Friends of the British Library">Friends of the British Library</a>, a charity set up to provide funding support to the <a href="British_Library" title="British Library">British Library</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-ar0607_9-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ar0607-9"><span>[</span>9<span>]</span></a></sup> He became a member of the <a href="Arts_Council_of_Great_Britain" title="Arts Council of Great Britain">Arts Council</a> Literature Panel in 1969, since becoming Chairman, and is an Honorary Fellow of the <a href="Royal_Society" title="Royal Society">Royal Society</a>.</p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="../../w/index-title=Melvyn_Bragg&action=edit&section=3.php.html" title="Edit section: Intellectual contributions">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Intellectual_contributions">Intellectual contributions</span></h2>
<p>Bragg has described the rise of a mass <a href="Intelligentsia" title="Intelligentsia">intelligentsia</a> in Britain.<sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10"><span>[</span>10<span>]</span></a></sup> He is credited with coining that term in common consciousness, an expression that was earlier used only in specialist sociological studies.</p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="../../w/index-title=Melvyn_Bragg&action=edit&section=4.php.html" title="Edit section: Personal life">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Personal_life">Personal life</span></h2>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:102px;"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Melvyn_bragg_head_crop.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5b/Melvyn_bragg_head_crop.jpg/100px-Melvyn_bragg_head_crop.jpg" width="100" height="144" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5b/Melvyn_bragg_head_crop.jpg/150px-Melvyn_bragg_head_crop.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5b/Melvyn_bragg_head_crop.jpg/200px-Melvyn_bragg_head_crop.jpg 2x" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Melvyn_bragg_head_crop.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="http://bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
Bragg in 2011</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Bragg married his first wife, Marie-Elisabeth Roche, in 1961,<sup id="cite_ref-mbceotv_2-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-mbceotv-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> and they had one child, a daughter.<sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11"><span>[</span>11<span>]</span></a></sup> Ten years later she killed herself. He did not know that his wife had a history of suicide attempts. "I could have done things which helped and I did things which harmed", he told <i>The Guardian</i> in 1998. "So yes, I feel guilt, I feel remorse."<sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12"><span>[</span>12<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Bragg's second wife, Catherine Mary Haste, whom he married in 1973,<sup id="cite_ref-mbceotv_2-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-mbceotv-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> is also a television producer and writer, having, among other things, edited the 2007 memoir of <a href="Clarissa_Eden" title="Clarissa Eden" class="mw-redirect">Clarissa Eden</a>, widow of Sir <a href="Anthony_Eden" title="Anthony Eden">Anthony Eden</a>, and collaborated with <a href="Cherie_Booth" title="Cherie Booth" class="mw-redirect">Cherie Booth</a>, wife of <a href="Tony_Blair" title="Tony Blair">Tony Blair</a>, on a 2004 book about the wives of British Prime Ministers. They have a son and a daughter.</p>
<p>Bragg has publicly discussed two nervous breakdowns that happened in his life, one in his teens, and another in his 30s.<sup id="cite_ref-smh.com.au_13-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-smh.com.au-13"><span>[</span>13<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>A friend of <a href="Tony_Blair" title="Tony Blair">Tony Blair</a>, the former Labour <a href="Prime_Minister_of_the_United_Kingdom" title="Prime Minister of the United Kingdom">Prime Minister</a>, in 1998 Bragg was named in a list of the largest private financial donors to the <a href="Labour_Party_(UK)" title="Labour Party (UK)">Labour Party</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14"><span>[</span>14<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>He is a supporter of <a href="Arsenal_F.C." title="Arsenal F.C.">Arsenal F.C.</a><sup id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-15"><span>[</span>15<span>]</span></a></sup> and Carlisle United (London Branch Hon President)</p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="../../w/index-title=Melvyn_Bragg&action=edit&section=5.php.html" title="Edit section: Selected honours and awards">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Selected_honours_and_awards">Selected honours and awards</span></h2>
<div class="refbegin references-column-count references-column-count-2" style="-moz-column-count: 2; -webkit-column-count: 2; column-count: 2;">
<ul>
<li><a href="Writers'_Guild" title="Writers' Guild" class="mw-redirect">Writers' Guild</a> Screenplay Award (1966)<sup id="cite_ref-mbceotv_2-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-mbceotv-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><a href="Mail_on_Sunday/John_Llewellyn_Rhys_Prize" title="Mail on Sunday/John Llewellyn Rhys Prize" class="mw-redirect">Mail on Sunday/John Llewellyn Rhys Prize</a> for <i>Without a City Wall</i> (1968)</li>
<li><a href="../../w/index-title=Time_Life_Silver_Pen_Award&action=edit&redlink=1.php.html" class="new" title="Time/Life Silver Pen Award (page does not exist)">Time/Life Silver Pen Award</a><sup id="cite_ref-mbceotv_2-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-mbceotv-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> for <i>The Hired Man</i> (1970)</li>
<li>Northern Arts Association Prose Award (1970)</li>
<li>Broadcasting Guild Award (1984)</li>
<li><a href="Ivor_Novello_Awards" title="Ivor Novello Awards">Ivor Novello Musical Award</a> (1985)<sup id="cite_ref-mbceotv_2-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-mbceotv-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>President of the <a href="National_Campaign_for_the_Arts" title="National Campaign for the Arts">National Campaign for the Arts</a> (since 1986)</li>
<li>British Academy of Film and Television Arts Dimbleby Award (1986)<sup id="cite_ref-mbceotv_2-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-mbceotv-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>Honorary Degree from the <a href="Open_University" title="Open University">Open University</a> as Doctor of the University. (1989)</li>
<li>Domus Fellow, <a href="St_Catherine's_College,_Oxford" title="St Catherine's College, Oxford">St Catherine's College, Oxford</a> (1990)</li>
<li><a href="Bad_Sex_in_Fiction_Award" title="Bad Sex in Fiction Award" class="mw-redirect">Bad Sex in Fiction Award</a> for <i>A Time to Dance</i> (1993)</li>
<li><a href="BAFTA" title="BAFTA" class="mw-redirect">BAFTA</a> TV Award for <i>An Interview with <a href="Dennis_Potter" title="Dennis Potter">Dennis Potter</a></i> (1995)</li>
<li>Honorary Fellowship from Wadham College, Oxford (1995)</li>
<li>Stretford Grammar Paired Reading Program, Stretford (1996)</li>
<li>Governor of the <a href="London_School_of_Economics" title="London School of Economics">London School of Economics</a> (since 1997).</li>
<li>Bragg was appointed to the <a href="House_of_Lords" title="House of Lords">House of Lords</a> as "Baron Bragg, of Wigton in the County of Cumbria"; <a href="Labour_Party_(UK)" title="Labour Party (UK)">Labour</a> <a href="Life_peer" title="Life peer" class="mw-redirect">life peer</a> (1998)<sup id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-16"><span>[</span>16<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-17"><span>[</span>17<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>Appointed Chancellor of the <a href="University_of_Leeds" title="University of Leeds">University of Leeds</a> (1999)</li>
<li><a href="WH_Smith_Literary_Award" title="WH Smith Literary Award">WH Smith Literary Award</a> for <i>The Soldier's Return</i> (2000)</li>
<li>Namesake of <a href="Millom" title="Millom">Millom</a> School drama studio (2005)<sup id="cite_ref-18" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-18"><span>[</span>18<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><a href="../../w/index-title=The_South_Bank_Show_Lifetime_Achievement_Award&action=edit&redlink=1.php.html" class="new" title="The South Bank Show Lifetime Achievement Award (page does not exist)">The South Bank Show Lifetime Achievement Award</a> (2010)</li>
<li><a href="BAFTA_Academy_Fellowship_Award" title="BAFTA Academy Fellowship Award">BAFTA Academy Fellowship Award</a> (2010)<sup id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19"><span>[</span>19<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>Honorary Fellowship of the <a href="British_Academy" title="British Academy">British Academy</a> (2010), for "public understanding of the arts, literature and sciences"<sup id="cite_ref-ba2010_1-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ba2010-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>Honorary Fellowship of <a href="Royal_Society" title="Royal Society">Royal Society</a> (2010)<sup id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-20"><span>[</span>20<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
</ul>
</div>
<ul>
<li>"Son of War", "Crossing The Lines" and "A Place in England" all long-listed for the Man Booker Prize</li>
</ul>
